comments: To specify on the questions where I ranked how positively I felt about my decisions: I wasn't sure if you were asking if I felt positively about the action or positively about my decision (which is very hard to gauge. Just because I feel that something is permissible, it's difficult to say whether I feel it is a positive or negative thing. These are complex issues). Also, you kept using the term hero and anti-hero back and forth, but the original definition was for anti-hero, so I based my first set of answers on that. However, it was unclear whether it was more of a question whether an anti-hero would do the things that were asked, or if it was somehow more acceptable for an anti-hero to do these things than the average person. In both cases, my judgments of right and wrong were pretty consistent. Hope this helps.

hero.typical.prime.roles: My incredibly-simplified definition: this is the character who you hope to see “win.” While it’s fine to think of Superman, or Aladdin, the hero doesn’t have to be noble, or courageous, or especially talented. As long as you’re rooting for him, that’s what matters.
hero.typical.prime.looks: The portrayal of movie superheroes may influence gender-related attitudes and behaviors, and reify socially constructed gender norms. Media portrayals communicate behavioral norms for both males and females (Paek, Nelson, & Vilela, 2011) and have potential to affect behaviors and attitudes.
hero.typical.prime.behave: The genesis and backgrounds of Superman and Batman are then examined—who they are, how they came to be superheroes, and what motivated them to become crime-fighters. This is followed by an assessment of the social context within which each superhero operates—the social structure of their society—specifically focusing on the worlds they inhabit.

anti.exemplar.prime.name: fox mulder (from the "x files")
anti.exemplar.prime.roles: fox mulder, along with  his partner dana scully, were the star characters  of the "X Files." whereas scully was very methodical with her decisions and never seemed to be very happy or very sad, mulder was the type who knew what had to be done and did it without worrying very much about consequences.  he was quite willing to act immorally, and sometimes illegally, if he thought it would lead to good results.
anti.exemplar.prime.looks: fox mulder (played by david ducuvney (sorry about butchering the spelling of his last name), was extremely handsome.  he certainly didn't look like a typical F.B.I. agent would look.  he looked good if he was dressed formally, and he looked just as good if he was wearing one of his new york knick tee-shirts.   his hair was always neatly combed.  he was neither very tall nor very short.
anti.exemplar.prime.behave: fox mulder went into his assignments with the attitude that he was going to succeed.  he was sort of arrogant, but not in a very negative way.  he knew he was good at what he did.  a key to mulder was that he really didn't care what people thought about his or his actions.  if you liked him, that was good.  but if you didn't like him, he wouldn't worry for one second about it.  although he was not interested in making enemies, he knew that part of his job was questioning things that hardly anyone questioned.  this did not bother him; in fact he seemed at times to relish the role of standing alone for his beliefs.  he was mocked by his peers for his beliefs and it didn't bother him because he expected it.  the poster in his office which we saw so often stating "trust no one" spoke volumes because mulder knew that he had a very difficult job and could never accept anything at face value if he was to succeed.
